ess in America. In Oil Cities, Henry Wiencek uncovers what life was like amidst the tent cities, saloons, and oil derricks of North Louisiana’s oil boomtowns, tracing the local experiences of migrants, farmers, sex workers, and politicians as they navigated dizzying changes to their communities. This first historical monograph on the region’s dramatic oil boom reveals a contested history, in which the oil industry had to adapt its labor, tools, and investments to meet North Louisiana’s unique economic, social, political, and environmental dynamics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxViolence againstzLouisianaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCities and townszLouisianaxGrowthxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand tenurezLouisianaxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aOil well drilling rigsxSocial aspectszLouisianaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezLouisianaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPetroleum workerszLouisianaxSocial conditionsxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aOil Production, Energy History, Natural Gas, American South, Huey Long, Ku Klux Klan, Louisiana politics, Environmental History, Industrialization, History of slavery, History of Race, Labor, Social History, Texas, Gender.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32917740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477329184/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles